	(52,1,'2016-06-09 09:08:48','2016-06-09 09:08:48','[:sr]<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rubrika Zentoteka integralni je deo Zent časopisa. Obzirom da će štampana tematska izdanja časopisa izlaziti dva puta godišnje, rubrika je zamišljena kao prostor u okviru koga će se redovno objavljivati eseji, kritike, analize, prikazi, prevodi, intervjui, ali i proza, poezija, i vizuelni radovi.</span></p><p>Zentoteka je u stalnoj potrazi za objavljenim i neobjavljenim radovima iz domena društvene teorije, politike, filozofije, arhitekture, tehnologije, kulture i umetnosti. Sve teme, ideje i oblici izražavanja su dobrodošli ukoliko su na liniji progresivnog kritičnog promišljanja stvarnosti i ukoliko su situirani na bilo kojoj od mnoštva instanci koje za okvir uzimaju ljudsku emancipaciju i težnju za izgradnjom slobodarskog, solidarnog i besklasnog društva, ili ukratko Smrt Fašizmu, Sloboda Narodu!</p><p>Zent ne veruje u objektivnost, neutralnost i apolitičnost</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent ne postavlja granice, već ih ispituje</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent je izvan žanrovskih ograničenja i postojećih uređenja</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent je za svakoga i za sve </span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tekstovi pisani u esejističkog formi ne bi trebalo da sadrže više od 3000 reči, poželjno je takođe da imaju što manje fusnota i referenci. Tekstovi mogu biti napisani na srpsko-hrvatskom ili engleskom jeziku.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Šaljite nam svoje tekstove, radove i/ili ideje na </span><a href=\"mailto:zentmagazine@gmail.com\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">zentmagazine@gmail.com</span></a></p><p>Radujemo se budućoj saradnji!</p><p>&nbsp;</p>[:en]<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zentoteka is an integral part of Zent magazine. Given that the printed thematic issues of Zent will be published twice a year, Zentoteka is a dedicated space for regular publication of essays, analysis, translations, interviews, as well as prose, poetry, and visual artworks.</span></p><p>Zentoteka is constantly looking for both unpublished and published contributions from the fields of social theory, politics, philosophy, architecture, technology, culture and art. All topics, ideas and forms of expression are welcome in so far as they are in line with progressive critical reflection of reality and as they are situated in any of the multiple instances that take human emancipation and aspire to liberation, solidarity and a classless society as their starting point, or in short Death to fascism, freedom to the people!</p><p>Zent does not believe in objectivity, neutrality and apolitical stances</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent does not set boundaries, but examines them</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent is beyond genre limitations and currently-existing conventions</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent is for everybody and for all</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Texts written in essayistic form should not exceed 3000 words, they should also contain as few as possible footnotes and references. Texts can be submitted in Serbo-Croatian or English.</span></p><p>Send your essays, pieces and/or ideas at zentmagazine@gmail.com</p><p>We look forward to our future cooperation!</p>[:]','[:sr]Stalno otvoren poziv[:en]Submit to Zentotheque[:]','','publish','closed','closed','','stalno-otvoren-poziv','','','2016-07-12 13:27:27','2016-07-12 13:27:27','',0,'http://localhost/ZentZent/zent/app/?post_type=otvoreni_pozivi&#038;p=52',0,'otvoreni_pozivi','',0),
	(53,1,'2016-06-09 09:09:21','2016-06-09 09:09:21','[:sr]<p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Danas kada nam država poručuje da smo lenji i da još od malih nogu treba da se pripremamo za okrutno globalno tržište u koje ćemo izgleda već kao četvoronošci biti bačeni, danas kada nam sa TV programa, fakultetskih govornica i stranica </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">lifestyle</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> magazina poručuju da ne možemo da radimo ako ne popravimo svoje ponašanje, ne promenimo svoje stavove i ne napunimo svoje CV-jeve neplaćenim </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">internship-</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">ima, danas kada ne samo da moramo da radimo nego moramo i da volimo to što radimo, kada moramo da budemo nasmejani i veseli na svojim radnim mestima, danas kada je poslovni uspeh gotovo jedino merilo ostvarenosti, a neuspeh uvek i isključivo naša lična krivica, danas kada je obrazovanje svedeno na obuku za posao, kada je i slobodno vreme postalo produktivno, kada je međuljudska komunikacija komodifikovana, danas kada se ostaci kulta radnika nekadašnje socijalne (socijalističke) države transformišu u kult rada kao takvog, u pustinji post socijalizma, pitanja šta je to uopšte rad, a šta je posao, kao i kako, zbog čega i pod kojim uslovima radimo, pitanja su koja stoje nad nama kao kakav džinovki neonski bilbord na vrhu stambenog solitera. Mi koji živimo u tim soliterima, u stanovima svojih roditelja, u tuđim stanovima koje sve teže sebi možemo da priuštimo, u stanovima koje smo kupili na kredit i za koje sada robujemo nemilosrdnim bankama, mi za koje gubitak posla znači gubitak osnovnih uslova za život, se pitamo šta kog đavola uopšte možemo da (u)radimo?</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">U sledećem broju Zenta, koji je posvećen pitanju rada, želimo da ispitamo i analiziramo transformacije koje su dovele do sadašnje opsednutosti radom i poslom, da problematizujemo koncepte i teorije, kao i da predložimo nove ideje i nova značenja.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Zent ne veruje u nade novouspostavljene ideologije fleksibilnog, privremenog i projektnog rada koji nam navodno pruža mogućnost izbora. Ko je ikada bio samozaposlen zna da samozaposlenje vodi u samoeksploataciju - uvek više a ipak uvek nedovoljno. Retki su srećnici kojima ova praksa ne pada teško ali ne možemo svi biti programeri, a i nećemo. Nametnut bestidnim ujedinjenjem države i kapitala, neoliberalni projekat nam se predstavlja kao nova sloboda za pojedinca. Međutim, otvorena i prikrivena eksploatacija, postepeno sistematsko uništavanje poslednjih kolektivnih mehanizama sigurnosti i ljudske reprodukcije - od zdravstva, do stanovanja i obrazovanja, odnosno gotovo potpuno prepuštanje pojedinaca samima sebi koje je praćeno rastućom zavisnošću od ličnih veza, poznanstava i/ili platformski posredovane \'reputacije\', kao i nepromenjeni odnosi nejednakosti na radnom mestu i u društvu i sve izrazitije ukidanje prava zaposlenih, druga su strana ovog sada već izlizanog novčića.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Sa druge strane, Zent ne veruje ni u jednostavan povratak na stabilna i sigurna radna mesta i kompromis „pune zaposlenosti“ koji je udario temelje posleratnoj nacionalnoj državi blagostanja ili socijalističkoj državi u domaćem kontekstu. Postojeći parametri merenja društvenog razvoja od BDP-a do prosečne plate više nam ništa ne govore. U vremenu kada tržišna ekonomija proizvodi enormne količine suvišne populacije, kada iz sopstvene krize izlazi ne stvarajući obećana nova radna mesta, zaposleni su raspršeni i neujedinjeni a nezaposleni saterani u sirotinjske kvartove i geta. Samoubistva radnika Foxconna i rapidno opadanje životnog standarda čak i za srednje klase globalnog Severa lokalne su manifestacije istog globalnog procesa - ultimativnog oslobađanja kapitala od radnika odnosno generisanje nepregledne armije rezervnog rada.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Pitanje šta je rad od posebnog je značaja danas kada suočeni sa razvojem napredne robotike, koja bi uskoro mogla zameniti sav rutinski ali i veliki deo nerutinskog ljudskog rada, po prvi put možemo da mislimo redistribuciju društvenog dobra na bazi univerzalnog osnovnog dohotka, time otvarajući vrata mogućnosti organizacije društva sa one strane rada. Rad kao smisao i svrha ljudi toliko je ukorenjen u nas da će se u susretu sa idejom njegove automizacije ljudi pitati: Čemu služe ljudi? Kojom etikom zameniti radnu etiku, šta postaje rad kada ne moramo više da radimo da bismo preživeli, ili u mnogo gorem ali i mnogo izvesnijem scenariju kako preživeti kada posla (zaposlenja) više nema? Brisanje granice između rada i života, tj. između radnog i slobodnog vremena već je uveliko uzelo maha… Pitanje kako oblikovati ovo sada jedinstveno vreme, odnosno spekulisanje o potencijalu budućeg dobijenog vremena, o izgradnji drugačijeg društva i života svakog pojedinca čini se ključnim. Možemo li jednostavno slediti naša slobodno izabrana zanimanja, opsesije, hobije i strasti, ili ćemo pak nastaviti u pravcu njihove apsolutne komodifikacije, u pravcu koji slobodno vreme pa čak i međuljudske odnose (druženje) pretvara u potencijalnu monetarnu vrednost.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zent veruje u mogućnosti povratka na pokušaje izgradnje solidarnog i besklasnog društva, kroz afirmaciju njihovih egalitarnih dosega, na način da taj povratak razume kao nastavak rada i borbe, </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">update</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, i ponovno reformulisanje egalitarnog društva. Zent vas poziva da spekulišete o ovom potencijalnom prostoru slobode od posla ili pak obrnuto borbe protiv invazije posla u slobodno vreme, kao i novim pitanjima vezanim za drugačije organizovanje društva bez rada. Kako ćemo deliti ono preostalo obaveznog rada u novom društvu? Šta postaje odgovornost? Napomene da nije moguće sav rad automatizovati, od čuvanja dece i brige za starima, do novih obaveza unutar zajednice, zahtevaju i nove odgovornosti i obaveze svakoga od nas. Na kraju možemo se zapitati i šta je danas rad (ukoliko uopšte postoji) koji nije podvrgnut tržišnoj razmeni, šta je rad jedne umetnice/umetnika, pesnikinje/pesnika, filozofkinje/filozofa, naučnice/naučnika, šta je angažovani rad, entuzijazam i odakle dolazi volja i želja za njim.</span></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><strong>Praktične smernice</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Svi oblici izražavanja su dobrodošli - arhitektonski projekti, radovi iz oblasti prirodnih i društvenih nauka, tehnologije, stripovi, ilustracije, intervjui, fotografije, istraživanja, vizuelni radovi, radovi umetnika i radovi radnika, poezija, proza, kao i teorijski i esejistički tekstovi. Tekstovi pisani u esejističkog formi ne bi trebalo da sadrže više od 3000 reči, a poželjno je takođe da imaju što manje fusnota i referenci. Tekstovi mogu biti napisani na srpsko-hrvatskom ili engleskom jeziku.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rok za podnošenje predloga je 15.08.2016. Izabrani autori/ke će biti pozvani da svoje gotove tekstove/radove dostave do 01.10.2016. Svoje predloge šaljite na </span><a href=\"mailto:zentmagazine@gmail.com\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">zentmagazine@gmail.com</span></a></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Radujemo se budućoj saradnji!</span></p>[:en]<p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Today when the State itself is telling us that we are lazy and that we should as early as children be prepared to be thrown into the cruel global market, today when everything from TV programmes and lifestyle magazines to university professors instructs us that we can’t work unless we adjust our behaviour, change our attitudes and fill-up our CVs with unpaid internships, today when we are not only obliged to work but should also love it, when we must be cheerful and happy at our workplaces, today when commercial success is the only measure of achievement and failure to succeed exclusively our own fault, today when education is reduced to job training, when leisure has become productive, when human relation and interaction has been commodified, today when the leftovers of the workers cult of the former social (socialist) state are increasingly transformed into the cult of work as such, in this post-socialist desert, the question what is work, and what is labour, as well as how, why and under what conditions we work, stands above us like some sort of giant neon billboard standing on top of a residential building. We who live in these buildings, in our parents’ apartments, renting someone else\'s apartments that we can no longer afford, in apartments we paid with debt for, we for whom the loss of a job means the loss of basic means for survival, wonder what the hell can we at all do?</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">In the next issue of Zent dedicated to the question of work, we wish to explore, investigate and analyze the transformations that brought about the contemporary obsession with work, to question concepts and theories and to suggest new ideas and new meanings.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Zent does not believe in the hopes of newly established ideology of flexible, temporary and project-driven work which supposedly offers numerous choices. Anyone who’s ever been self-employed knows that self-employment leads to self-exploitation - ever more but never enough. Rare are those whom this does not pose a great burden, but we cannot all become developers, and we don’t want to. Imposed by the shameless union between capital and the state, this neoliberal project is being represented as the new freedom for the individual. However, open and disguised exploitation, gradual systematic destruction of collective mechanisms that previously facilitated human reproduction - from health to housing and education, i.e. the imperative of individual self-sufficiency which is accompanied by the increasing dependency on personal connections, contacts and networks as well as platform-facilitated ‘reputation’, together with the unchanged relationships of inequality in the working place and in society and the pronounced suppression of workers’ rights, represent the other side of this now already worn-out coin.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">On the other hand, Zent does not believe in the simple return to stable and secure working positions and the compromise of ‘full employment’ that laid the foundation of the post-war national welfare or socialist state. Existing parameters measuring social development from GDP to average salary do not tell us anything no more. In the time when market economy is producing enormous quantities of surplus populations, when it’s coming out of its crisis without producing the promised new jobs, the employed are dispersed and scattered and the unemployed pushed aside, herded into urban slams and ghettos. The suicides of Foxconn workers and rapidly declining living standards even for the middle classes of the global North represent local manifestations of the same global process - the capital’s ultimate disposal of workers, or put differently the hyperproduction of an endless reserve army of labor. </span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">The questions pertaining to the issue of work are especially important today when faced with the development of advanced robotics that could shortly replace all routine and even most of non-routine human labour, for the first allows us to think redistribution of social wealth on the basis of universal basic income, thereby opening up the possibility of contemplating the organization of society beyond work. Work as something which gives meaning and purpose is rooted in us to the extent that faced with its automation people are ought to wonder: What are we for? By which ethics we are to replace the working ethics, what does work become when we are no longer obliged to work in order to survive, or in much worse but much more convincing scenario - how to survive when work i.e. jobs are no longer available? The fading of difference between work and life, or more precisely between work and leisure has already taken place… Speculations on how to shape this now singular time, i.e. on the potential of this future time liberated from work, about the possibility to build a different society and different life of each individual, seem to be crucial. Could we simply follow our freely chosen interest, professions and obsessions, hobbies and passions, or will we rather continue in the direction of their absolute commodification, in the direction that transforms leisure and even interpersonal relations into potential sources of income? </span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Zent believes in the possibility of returning to the attempts of building a solidary and classless society through the affirmation of their egalitarian principles, whereas this return is understood as continuation of work and struggle, an update and re-formulation of the idea of an egalitarian society. Zent invites you to speculate about the potential of life liberated from work or the other way around, about the struggle against the invasion of work into leisure and life, as well as about new questions related to organization of society without work. How to divide amongst ourselves the obligatory work that remains? What does responsibility become? Remarks that not all work can be automated, from care work to new obligations within a community, demand new responsibilities and duties that each of us must take on. In the end, we may also wonder, what is work today (if it exists at all) that is not subjected to market exchange, what is the work of an artist, poet, philosopher, scientist, what is engaged work, enthusiasm and where does the will and desire for it come from?</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Practical Guidelines</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">All forms of expression and approaches are welcome - architectural projects, natural and social sciences, technology, comics, illustrations, interviews, photography, research findings, visual and artistic interventions, works of art and works of workers, poetry, prose, as well as theoretical and essayistic formats. Texts written in essayistic form should not exceed 3000 words, they should also contain as few as possible footnotes and references. Texts can be submitted in Serbo-Croatian or English.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Proposals should be submitted by August 15 2016. Selected authors will be invited to submit their full texts/pieces by October 10 2016. Send your proposals to </span><a href=\"mailto:zentmagazine@gmail.com\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">zentmagazine@gmail.com</span></a></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">We look forward to our future cooperation!</span></p>[:]','[:sr]ZENT #02 Rad - Otvoren poziv[:en]ZENT #02 Work - Open Call[:]','','publish','closed','closed','','zent-02-rad-otvoren-poziv','','','2016-07-12 13:27:47','2016-07-12 13:27:47','',0,'http://localhost/ZentZent/zent/app/?post_type=otvoreni_pozivi&#038;p=53',0,'otvoreni_pozivi','',0),
