	(269,1,'2016-11-07 20:29:46','2016-11-07 20:29:46','[:sr]<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nakon<span>[fusnota]Tekst je izvorno predstavljen na globalnom umetničkom forumu Art Dubai \" Menadžment razočarenja: umetnici i publika\", održanom u Ujedinjenim Arapskim Emiratima marta 2011. godine, a potom objavljen u Iranskom časopisu Art Tomorrow, br. 4, proleće 2011, strana 172-181. Ovde preveden i objavljen uz dozvolu autora.</span><span>[/fusnota]</span> noćnog leta srednje dužine, odlazeći ili dolazeći na sledeći sastanak/ konsultaciju/konferenciju/simpozijum/ gig/vikend u gradu, upadaš u taksi. Osećaš privremeno olakšanje što barem možeš sa vozačem da proćaskaš na svom maternjem ili pak drugom jeziku koji najbolje poznaješ. Međutim, iznenada si zbunjen jer postaje jasno da vozač svakako ne razume šta si rekao, i da ni jedan od jezika koji obično govoriš njemu nije razumljiv. Gde si ti beše? Ponovo mu daješ adresu, ovog puta bez upotrebe pretpostavljenog zajedničkog govornog aparata, i kako vozač odmiče od aerodroma uveren si da iako nisi odrastao ovde, ovo mesto do sada već dovoljno dobro poznaješ. Sve je onako kako se sećaš, sa još po nekim novim oblakoderom, nastavkom gradnje u okolini aerodroma i sa još nekoliko internacionalnih lanaca prodavnica koje oblažu spoljašnja predgrađa grada. </span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zbog radova na novoj liniji lakog metroa koji povezuje grad sa aerodromom, radova koji se, kako izgleda, nikada neće završiti, dolazi do zastoja u saobraćaju, tako da igrom srećnih okolnosti vozač nastavlja zaobilaznim putem i dovodi te u deo grada za koji si čuo ali nikada do sada nisi imao prilike da posetiš. Nekada zapušten, poznat po propalim i zatvorenim prodavnicama i malim fabrikama, sada je našminkan nekolicinom kafića, restorana, galerija, butika i klubova, diskretno najavljujući deo onoga u šta se ovaj kraj pretvara. Skromni izlozi skrivaju ponudu, promovišući tako veću prisnost sa robom unutar same prodavnice. Dovoljno dobro si upoznat sa svim ovim strategijama. Još uvek u raskoraku sa, džet legom iseckanim, nervnim sistemom, odlučuješ da napraviš samo mentalnu belešku nekoliko mesta na koje ćeš se vratiti nakon što završiš sa pripremama i sastancima koji ti slede. Sa sajta dobro upućenog city guide-a, koji si bukmarkovao na tvom inače beskorisnom iPad-u saznaćeš već gde vredi otići. U međuvremenu nastavljaš da sa upola pažnje gledaš kroz prozor taksija, primećujući da je sva odeća u izlozima koja se prodaje kao unikatna, ista kao iz mesta iz koga si upravo došao i nekog drugog gde ćeš otići za nekih deset dana. Mikro-lokalna verzija globalnog brenda šik jakne koju upravo nosiš.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zaustavljajući se na semaforu samo trenutak pre izlaska iz ovog kraja nalaziš sebe zagledanog kroz prozor taksija u umetničko delo postavljeno na oko 3 metra unutar, neonskim svetlom, osvetljene galerije. Tvoja prva pomisao je da te rad na neki udaljen način podseća na komad koji ti je privukao pažnju u jednom umetničkom magazinu prošlog meseca. Ne sećaš se ni umetnika ni izložbe, jedino da je glavni kurator LACMA-e bio na otvaranju. Počinješ da skrećeš pogled sa galerijskog prostora, kao i sa svih drugih prozora i izloga, jedva čekajući samo da dođeš u svoj apartman, da se istuširas, organizuješ, možda na kratko odspavaš ili treniraš pre prvog sastanka koji ti sledi za četiri sata.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Međutim, takođe zatičes sebe kako i dalje gledaš u ovaj rad, primećujući, samo nekoliko trenutaka pre nego što će se taksi udaljiti, ime umetnika napisano Helvetika stensil slovima</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">na prozoru, i ispod i sa desne strane, ime galerije za koju bez previše iznenađenja saznaješ da se preselila sa prethodne, pomalo izolovane lokacije. Prisećaš se toga bez obzira na nelagodnost koju osećaš jer si je, još pre osam meseci, ipak već tražio i zapravo skoro doneo neki art tamo. Iako to nije baš ispalo kako treba, uspostavio si dobar odnos sa galeristkinjom - ti si verovao njoj i ona je verovala tebi u dovoljnoj meri da budeš smatran kolekcionarom jednog od njenih bolje poznatih umetnika. Dopala ti se njena ozbiljnost i zahvalnost zbog tvog interesovanja za umetnost i dizajn u tako mnogo gradova.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kasnije tog dana, kada si došao sebi od posledica puta, nalaziš sebe kako si sa vremena na vreme zaokupljen galerijama, kvartovima grada, umetnošću. Čekirajući lokalni art vodič na svom iPad-u saznaješ da ona ista galerija koju si primetio iz taksija večeras ima otvaranje i, nakon par SMS-ova, ažuriranja svog Facebook i Twiter profila, dogovaraš da se nađes tamo</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">sa prijateljicom. Međutim ne vidiš to samo kao neko mesto za sastajanje. Ostao si zaintrigiran onim kratkim iskustvom umetničkog rada koje si imao: njegova postavka u prostoru ukazala je na inteligentnost i samosvest; utisak koji si dobio, činio ti se samo kao stvar trenutka, dok si takođe prepoznao da je igra formi u radu duboko usađena u jedan kulturni žargon koji ti se dopada i kao da je izgledalo da cela stvar traži više od tebe kako bi se konačno zaokružila. Za razliku od robe iz obližnjih prodavnica koja se, kao što to veoma dobro razumeš, obraća tebi tako da govori nešto o tvojoj potrošnji, ova umetnost izgleda kao da traži nešto od tebe. Rad te intrigira. Želiš ponovo da ga vidiš. Razmišljaš da ga kupiš.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Međutim nisi baš siguran: iako znaš da ova vrsta umetnosti dobija na popularnosti, ipak si video ovaj komad samo na trenutak, a umetnica ti je nepoznata. Čekiraš ArtFacts i saznaješ da je rangirana ne baš toliko nisko i to ti daje određeno samopouzdanje: izlagala je pomalo po inostranstvu, imala par izložbi u institucijama, međutim još uvek nije toliko priznata da bi joj cene bile nepristupačne. Umetnica je u usponu i shvatajući to, odjednom se osećaš pokrenut entuzijazmom, kojem se, samo nekoliko časova pre toga, nisi nadao. Podstaknut si da pozoveš galeriju i nakon par razmenjenih ljubaznih reči sa galeristkinjom ugovoraš sastanak malo pre otvaranja.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">U taksiju na putu prema galeriji, želiš još malo da se uveriš i šalješ informacije o umetnici svom savetniku za umetnost, nadajući se da je u vremenskoj zoni odakle će moći da ti odgovori na vreme pre nego što stigneš u galeriju. Imaš sreće: tvoj savetnik se nalazi na sajmu umetnost tri sata iza tebe i odmah odgovara - ‘Sent from my Blackberry’ – govoreći da iako postoje priče o ovoj umetnici, da se one trenutno svode samo na jedan ili dva grada; da je izložba na koju upravo ideš njena prva u regionu u kojem se nalaziš; da je veoma bitno to što galeristkinja koja ponovo otvara galeriju na novoj lokaciji, baš nju u ovom novom prostoru prikazuje, i još par tračeva koji te istovremeno uzbuđuju i dosadni su ti.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ne stižeš da razmisliš o svemu ovome a već si stigao, i kratko vreme si sam sa izložbom. Prošavši kroz prostor vraćaš se na rad koji si ugledao kroz staklo taksija, što ti sada izgleda danima daleko. Onakav je kakav ti je ostao u sećanju ali, pošto si razmišljao o njemu u satima pre dolaska, počinješ još više da ga ceniš, laknulo ti je, nalaziš da nastavlja da nagrađuje tvoju zainteresovanost za njega. Nalazeći najbolje uglove iz kojih ćeš ga posmatrati, kontemplirajući ga, ispitujući odnos između njegove ideje i forme, on hrani i zadovoljava tvoju radoznalost na način na koji smatraš da umetnost to radi najbolje. Voliš umetnost upravo zbog toga što ti daje vreme da pronađeš sopstveni put kroz nju.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Iako nisi ni primetio kada je došla, galeristkinja je već pored tebe. “Fantastičan rad”, izgovara tiho, zagledana u njega zajedno sa tobom. Nakon pozdrava i malo ćaskanja, ponovo pauza dok zajedno stojite zagledani u delo. Kažeš koliko ceniš ton i emociju samog dela, njegov senzibilitet. Galeristkinja ti odgovara da je to upravo ono što je tako važno u praksi ove umetnice, zajedno sa komuniciranjem i približavanjem tradicija umetnosti savremenoj publici, koje su, kako si to već prepoznao, inspiracija za umetnicu. Galeristkinja ti dalje govori da nam umetnica ukazuje na epohu u kojoj je izgledalo da umetnost ima centralno mesto u društvenim i estetskim promenama, odlučujući trenutak modernosti. Slažeš se: ovo umetničko delo približava te toj snazi, jednoj liniji transformacije koja ti se međutim sada ne nameće, dopuštajući ti da stvoriš sopstveni smisao samog dela. Pominješ galeristkinji ovaj zanimljivi odnos prema istoriji. Slaže se, i zadivljena tvojim entuzijazmom i poštovanjem za umetnost, insistira da prisustvuješ večeri nakon otvaranja. Ljubazno prihvataš i koristiš priliku da pokreneš razgovor o ceni dela. Galeristkinja nagoveštava da bi nešto bilo moguće srediti, ali imajući na umu sve faktore koje treba uzeti u obzir, kao i da ovo nije ni mesto ni vreme da se donese bilo kakva odluka, ali ipak primetivši tvoje očekivanje popusta, ona odlučuje da ti ga rezerviše.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kasnije tokom otvaranja galeristkinja te upoznaje sa umetnicom. Uprkos tvojoj želji da pričaš sa njom, opet si obeshrabren jer zapravo ne razumeš ništa što ti govori. Nemoguće da je u pitanju tvoj engleski, budući da si ga stekao obrazovanjem u najboljim američkim školama i njihovim ograncima u drugim zemljama, koliko i tvojim kosmopolitskim životom posle toga. Nije u pitanju to šta ona govori, jer iako ti jezik zvuči blisko ne možeš da uhvatiš značenje nijedne reči zbog akcenta. Tvoja zbunjenost raste jer umetnica ima anglosaksonsko ime, i mala grupa ljudi u kojoj se ti i ona sada nalazite je internacionalna tako da bi trebalo da se govori engleski. Nakon nekog vremena od nekoga iz grupe saznaješ da je ona škotlanđanka i postaje ti jasno zbog čega je nisi razumeo. Sad čak počinješ da hvataš poneku frazu. Umetnica izražava duboko poštovanje za relativno nepoznatog umetnika visokog modernizma, i drago ti je što si ranije uvideo nešto od toga u samom delu. Zaključuješ na osnovu reakcija drugih da umetnica prihvata različite ideje o značenju njenog rada jer želi da on bude otvoren interpretaciji publike, pozdravljajući razovrsnost gledišta. Zapravo je rasprava o radu, kaže ona, sa iznenadnom snagom i jasnoćom, sama suština njenog rada. Naravno čitava ova priča nije odlazila previše duboko, ipak je ovo samo otvaranje - međutim dovoljno je da te ponovo uveri da umetnost zaista poseduje jednu složenost ideja i emocija</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">do kojih ti je stalo, da iako ne poznaješ umetnicu lično ti uprkos tome možeš da osetiš neku vezu sa njom kroz njenu umetnost. Ona očekuje od svoje publike da bude inteligentna kao ti, uključujući te kao individuu. Prepoznaješ da će se njena interesovanja razvijati u pravcu koji bi mogao da slediš. Odlučuješ da joj ne spomeneš svoju zainteresovanost za komad, kako na otvaranju iznenada ne bi osetila nelagodnost sa tobom. U svakom slučaju, možete o tome da pričate još kada ona to bude pokrenula.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dok te voze na večeru priređenu povodom otvaranja izložbe, tvoja prijateljica te zamara njenim idejama o investiranju u kraj u kome se smestila galerija, korišćenju prilike koju grad pruža promenom zoniranja i smanjenjem taksi kako bi se podstakao rast malih kreativnih preduzeća, privukle strane investicije i tako dalje. Čuo si sve to već ranije i zvuči ti previše kao tvoj dnevni posao (ako ti je više uopšte i jasno šta znači “dnevni”, pored svih tih putovanja koja obavljaš). Suviše si uzbuđen zbog onoga što večeras sledi i ubrzo skrećeš razgovor na moguću kupovinu dela. Razmatraš sa prijateljicom koji bi od tvojih apartmana bio najbolje mesto za rad, ali si gotovo siguran da to treba da bude mesto na kojem ćeš provesti najviše vremena u godini koja dolazi. Često to radiš sa novim delima kako bi ti ona postala bliska, nagrađujući tvoju zaiteresovanost koja ne prestaje. Prepoznaješ međutim i da je otvaranjem ove izložbe, galeristkinja njen prostor uzdigla na nivo internacionalne umetničke scene, nimalo se ne ograničavajući lokalim interesima, da se o tom delu grada već pisalo u nekoliko vodiča koje si preleteo na svom iPad-u, i da je na otvaranju bilo krcato ne samo uobičajnom gomilom entuzijasta i namćorastim lokalnim umetnicima, već i nekim ljudima koji su došli u napucanim kolima, takođe podsećaš sebe da bi ipak trebalo pitati prijateljicu o lokalnim investicionim prilikama, jer se ovde nešto očigledno događa.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tokom večere osećaš olakšanje što ne sediš blizu umetnice jer i dalje ne možeš da skapiraš njen akcenat. Međutim dovoljno si blizu i nje i galeristkinje da se ne mogu osećati uvređeno. Uključuješ se u zanimljiv razgovor sa nekoliko lokalnih kolekcionara, umetnika i kritičara. Zanima ih tvoje mišljenje o radovima umetnice, o gradovima i umetničkim scenama u koje si dobro upućen, kao i tvoji stavovi o razvoju regiona u tom kontekstu. Jedana od kritičarki te poziva da daš intervju za njihov magazin, na temu dostupnosti i važnosti kolekcionarstva za razvoj kulturne ekonomije i identiteta regiona u vremenu globalizacije. Polaskan si, osećaš da ona razume da svi mi sada živimo u jednom povezanom svetu, da oseća kako tvoje interesovanje za umetnost komunicira ovu sveopštu povezanost, što ti omogućava da razmišljaš o odnosu između mesta iz koga ti dolaziš i mesta iz koga dolazi umetnik. Razbiraš sve to po glavi dok razmenjuješ vizit karte sa kritičarkom, radujući se trenutku kada ćeš joj pokazati svoju kolekciju. Kasnije čim se ukazala prilika da nasamo popričaš sa galeristkinjom, ugovaraš kupovinu. Bilo je to veoma dobro veče i napuštaš ga, sad već dovoljno ohrabren da pokušaš da uđeš čak i u direktan razgovor sa umetnicom.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dva meseca kasnije delo je postavljeno u tvom stanu, i za ono nekoliko puta koliko si bio tamo, primećuješ kako postaješ još više entuzijastičan sposobnostima umetnice da prizove najvažniju vrednost umetnosti na tako ličnom i neposrednom nivou. Razgovaraš sa svojim savetnikom za umetnost o tvojoj zadivljenosti ovom umetnicom i on ti predlaže da zajedno posetite njenu matičnu galeriju kako biste videli šta oni još imaju dostupno. Srećom posao te sledećeg meseca odvodi baš u taj grad i savetnik ti zakazuje sastanak. Dok si tamo saznaješ da trenutno ništa od njenih radova nije dostupno, ali da galerija planira da predstavi umetnicu na njihovom sledećem sajmu umetnosti. Izražavaš veliko interesovanje i uveravaš galeriju da će ti raspored omogućiti da budeš na sajmu. Na predotvaranju sajma, zahvaljujući tvojim vezama sa galeristkinjom sa kojom si prvobitno imao posla, obezbeđuješ sledeći komad po sniženoj ceni.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tri meseca kasnije: obezbedio si još jedan rad sa prve izložbe umetnice u Njujorku. Ne možeš da budeš tamo ali tvoj savetnik za umetnost sređuje detalje za tebe. Zadovoljan si što saznaješ da si jedan od vodećih kolekcionara radova ove umetnice: veruješ da je vredi podržati, da njen rad zaslužuje pažnju i vidljivost koju dobija u magazinima i časopisima, da sa njenom umetničkom inteligentnošću i osetilnošću nisi saglasan samo ti, već i tvoje kolege i prijatelji koji su većinom impresionirani njenom umetnošću, koja se sada već nalazi u više prostora u kojima živiš.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Godinu dana kasnije sa istinskim zadovoljstvom primaš poziv od matične galerije umetnice da za potrebe izložbe u muzeju jednog od glavnih metropolitskih centara pozajmiš jedno od njenih dela. Posebno si uzbuđen zato što je u pitanju jedan od gradova u kojem provodiš najviše vremena i već neko vreme ceniš izložbe tradicionalnih radova iz različitih regiona postavljenih zajedno sa delima savremene umetnosti koje taj isti muzej organizuje. Kad god si mogao da posetiš te izložbe, sa obzirom na tvoj gust raspored, bio si impresioniran pronalaženjem estetskih i kulturnih vrednosti koje te različite tradicije imaju u današnjem svetu. Bez ustezanja prihvataš pozajmicu koju organizuješ preko svog savetnika za umetnost. On obezbeđuje mesto za tebe i njega na ekskluzivnom ručku povodom otvaranja izložbe.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pored određene sumnje u to da li je umetnicin rad na najbolji način postavljen na izložbi, takođe shvataš da je prisustvo njenog rada na ovoj izložbi dobro za njen profil. Umetnica je</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">u isto vreme i pomalo nervozna i pomalo uzbuđena svojim prisustvom na izložbi. Imajući u vidu to da si uspeo donekle da shvatiš njen izgovor do sada, upuštaš se u neobavezan razgovor i razmenjuješ nekoliko šala sa njom kako bi je oraspoložio tokom formalnosti otvaranja. Tokom večere, ponovo zatičeš sebe kako sa entuzijazmom pričaš o tome koliko ceniš umetnicu, izložbu i muzej, o potrebi promocije istorije i tradicije umetnosti, i kako su muzeji pogodna mesta za to jer na kraju krajeva istorija i jeste njihov posao. Ostavljaš jak utisak na predstavnicu komisije muzeja za koju sa zadovoljstvom saznaješ da već zna nešto o tebi. I pored toga ipak si pomalo iznenađen (i zadovoljan) kada za otprilike mesec dana posle ove večere od nje dobijaš mejl u kome te poziva da prisustvuješ ručku sa prijateljima muzeja i njegovim direktorom. Na ručku, direktor muzeja napominje kako je od nedavno upražnjeno jedno mesto u odboru savetnika i pita te da razmotriš ponudu. Ti si naravno oduševljen ponudom ali se praviš pomalo nezainteresovan i odgovaraš jedino da ćeš razmisliti o tome. Direktor muzeja napominje da svaki takav izbor zavisi od formalnog poziva, procedure provere (iz razloga odgovornosti prema javnosti) a možda čak i panel diskusije. Ovaj odgovor izaziva određenu alarmantnost kod tebe. Da li je trebalo da budeš manje neodlučan u svom odgovoru? Uveravaš sebe da su ovo standardne procedure koje bi u svakom slučaju morale biti preduzete. I naravno, otprilike nedelju dana kasnije dobijaš pozivno pismo da postaneš savetnik muzeja koji od tebe traži da doprineseš njegovom budućem razvoju a na osnovu tvog velikog interesovanja za promociju savremene umetnosti. Prihvataš ovaj poziv prošavši kroz ritualne procese imenovanja sa sigurnošću i lakoćom. Upitan zbog čega želiš da preuzmeš dodatni napor koji dolazi sa tako malim obeštećenjem, nalaziš sebe kako razmišljaš o umetnosti koja te je isprva dovela u vezu sa muzejem i to ti daje samopouzdanje da na istinski i suštinski način govoriš o svojoj strasti i verovanju u ono što umetnost može da učini za pojedinca kao što si ti.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Uskoro nalaziš sebe kako koristiš znanje iz oblasti investicija i razvoja kako bi savetovao muzej u njegovoj strategiji proširenja. To te uzbuđuje obzirom da ti se čini da to znanje izgleda posebno korisno gledano prema parametrima onoga što ti misliš da je veoma važno u umetnosti danas: isticanje ličnog susreta sa njom, njenu otvorenost prema diskusiji, njen snažan edukativni aspekt kroz iznošenje važnih tema u javnost, bez da to čini nametljivo, njenu inkluzivnost. Ono što nastavlja da te inspiriše, uprkos ponekad dosadnom ali važnom poslu koji si pozvan da radiš, jeste to da je poslovanje muzeja sada u samom centru strategije razvoja regiona u kome muzej igra centralnu ulogu. Ti igraš svoju skromnu ali opet važnu ulogu u svemu tome. Promovišući javnu edukaciju koja je na odgovarajući način osetljiva prema kompleksnosti sveta, time što podržavaš ono što nalaziš da je najvrednije od umetnosti, osećaš da si pronašao nešto što te najbolje predstavlja u javnosti, nešto vredno truda, ne samo za tebe, već i za sve nas. </span></p>[:en]<p>Slumping<span>[fusnota]This article is based on a talk presented at \'Disappointment Management: Artists &amp; Audiences\', Global Art Forum_5, Art Dubai, UAE, March 14-18, 2011</span><span>[/fusnota]</span> into the taxi after your overnight medium-haul flight to or from the next board meeting/consultancy/conference/symposium/gig/weekend-city-break, you feel temporarily relieved to be able to at least speak to the driver in your native or second language. But then you’re suddenly confused because it’s clear that the driver doesn’t easily understand what you’ve said anyway and none of the languages you regularly use are his. So where are you again? You give him the address once more, this time without the conversational apparatus of familiarity, and as he pulls away from the airport you’re reassured that even if you didn’t grow up here you know this place fairly well by now. Everything is where you remember it, given one or two new towers, an extension of the development around the airport and a couple more international chain stores lining the outer suburbs of the city.</p><p>But the traffic’s grinding to a halt because the work on the new light-rail connection to the airport seems to be carrying on forever, so the driver takes a detour fortuitously bringing you into an area of the city you had heard of but not yet had a chance to visit. Formerly a bit battered, known for its closing and failing retail and light industrial businesses, it’s now peppered with a few cafes, restaurants, galleries, boutiques and clubs only discreetly announcing themselves to be, just as precisely, part of what is arriving, not leaving the area. The displays in what windows there are understate the cause of their merchandise, promoting the greater intimacy of your encounter with them within the boutiques. You’re familiar enough with all these strategies.</p><p>Still caught in the deferrals of your jet-lag shredded nervous-system, you decide to only make a mental note of one or two places you’ll return to later once you’re through the preparation and meetings directly ahead of you. You’ll find out where is worth going from the city insider guide website bookmarked on your otherwise disappointing iPad. Meantime, you continue to look half-curiously out of the taxi window, noting that though the clothes on display are all evidently made in the boutiques selling them as unique items, they’d have also worked really well where you just came from and where you’ll be going in about ten days. A micro-local version of the globally chic fashion-house diffusion-range jacket you’re wearing right now.</p><p>Stopping at a light just before you leave the area you find yourself gazing through the taxi window at an artwork placed about 3 meters into a neon-lit gallery space. Your first reaction is that it reminds you in a distant way of a piece that caught your attention in the art magazine newsletter last month. You don’t remember the artist or venue, only that the Chief Curator of LACMA was at the opening. You start to turn away from the gallery space as you have from all the other windows and fronts, looking forward now just to getting back to your place, to shower, organize yourself, maybe have a quick recuperative sleep or workout before your first meeting in four hours’ time. But you also find yourself continuing to look at this art, noting just before the cab pulls away the name of the artist, presented in Helvetica stencil-lettering on the window, and below it and to the right, that of the gallery which you are not too surprised to learn has moved from its previous slightly too isolated location. You recall that despite that inconvenience you nonetheless sought it out eight months ago and in fact nearly brought some art there. Even though that didn’t quite work out, you and the gallerist had a good rapport – you trusted her and she trusted you enough to be considered as a collector of one of her better known artists. You liked the seriousness and her appreciation of your interest in art and design in so many cities.</p><p>Later that day, having extricated yourself enough from the dislocations of travel, you find yourself occasionally pre-occupied with the gallery, the area, the art. Checking the local art guide on your iPad you find out that the gallery has its opening that evening and, after a few SMS’s, updates of your Facebook page and tweets, you arrange to meet a friend there. But you are not especially thinking about it as just a meeting place. You’ve remained intrigued by the glimpse of the work you had: its presentation in the space showed an intelligence and self-awareness; what images you could make out in it seemed somehow of the moment while you also recognized its play of forms to be rooted in the cultural vernaculars you like; and the way the whole thing seemed to want <u>more of you</u> for it to come together. Unlike the goods in the boutiques nearby which, as you understand very well, presents itself to you so as to say something about you in its consumption, this art seems to ask something of you. The work intrigues you. You want to see more of it. You think of buying it.</p><p>But you are not sure: while you know that this kind of art is beginning to get some exposure, you only saw this piece for less than a minute, and the artist is unfamiliar to you. You check ArtFacts and see that she is ranked in the low thousands and this gives you a certain confidence: she has shown a bit internationally, had a couple of exhibitions in public spaces, but is not established enough for her prices to be out of reach. The artist is on the way up and recognizing this suddenly propels you into an enthusiasm you didn’t think was available to you even a few hours before, spurring you to call the gallery and, after exchanging some pleasantries with the gallerist, arranging to meet her at the space just before the opening.</p><p>In the cab going to the gallery you seek some reassurance, emailing your art advisor about the artist, hoping that he is in a timezone where he will be able to answer you before you get there. You’re in luck: he’s at an artfair three hours behind you and answers immediately - ‘Sent from my Blackberry’ - saying that though there’s a buzz about the artist it’s still contained at the moment to one or two cities; that the show you are about to go to is the first in the region you are in; that it’s taken as a real sign of the gallerist having arrived that she is showing the artist in the new space; and some other gossip which simultaneously titillates and bores you.</p><p>Before you have time to process all of this, you arrive and you are alone with the show for a few minutes in the empty space. Taking a walk through it you return to the piece you saw through the taxi window from what now feels like days away. It is as you remember it but, having grown in your mind in the hours since arriving, you appreciate it more and, relieved, you find that it continues to reward your interest in it.  Finding the right places to see it from, exploring it in your mind, examining the interplay between its ideas and its forms, it feeds and satisfies your curiosity in the way you find art does best. You like art precisely because it gives you this time to find your way through it.</p><p>The gallerist is by your side without you noticing how she got there. ‘An amazing work’, she says quietly, gazing at it with you.  After some greetings and small talk, a pause as you both stare at the work again. You say how much you appreciate the tone and feel of the piece, its sensitivity. The gallerist tells you that this is exactly what is so important for the artist in her practice, together with humanizing for a contemporary audience the historical traditions of art that, as you have already recognized, were an inspiration for her. The gallerist says that the artist reminds us all of an epoch when art seemed central to social and aesthetic changes, a decisive moment of modernity. You agree: the artwork brings you close to that impetus, a vector of transformation yet one that now doesn’t force your hand, allowing you to make your own sense of the work. You mention this intriguing play with history to the gallerist. She agrees and, impressed with your enthusiasm and appreciation of the art, insists that you attend the aftershow dinner. You humbly acquiesce and take advantage of the opportunity to broach the subject of the price of the work. The gallerist suggests something may be possible but, given all the factors that need to be taken into account, and recognizing that this is not a place or time to resolve anything, you settle with her that she reserve it for you while noting your expectation of a discount.</p><p>Later at the opening, the gallerist introduces you to the artist. Despite your enthusiasm to talk to her, you are unnerved once more because you don’t really understand anything she is saying. It can’t be your English, since that has been honed by your graduate schooling in the best American schools and their offshore campuses, as much as the internationalism of your life since. And it isn’t anything she may saying because you just can’t make out any of the words through the accent. Your confusion is compounded since the artist has an Anglo name and the small group you and she are in are from the usual wide range of places and so are speaking English. Then you catch from someone in the group that she is Scottish and your incomprehension now makes sense to you. You can now even begin to pick out the occasional phrase. The artist expresses a deep appreciation of a relatively unknown high modernist and you are pleased that you understood something of this in the work. You gather from responses to what she is saying that she welcomes different ideas of what her work may be about because she wants it to be open to whatever the audience makes of it, welcoming the divergence of views on it. It is in fact the discussion of her work, she says with sudden force and clarity, that is the very point of the work.</p><p>Of course, none of this is taken up in too much depth — it is after all only the opening night — but it’s enough to reassure you that the art really has the complexity of ideas and sensitivity that matters to you, that even though you have little in common with her personally you can nonetheless share something through her art. She recognizes her audience to be intelligent as you are, engaging you as an individual. You intuit that her interests will develop in a way that you can stay with. You choose not to mention your interest in the piece to her in case she would suddenly feel uncomfortable with you at the opening. In any case, you can always speak more about it when she installs it.</p><p>Being driven to the after-show dinner, your friend tires you with her interest in investing in the area the gallery has set up in, taking advantage of the rezoning and tax breaks offered by the city to encourage small-scale creative enterprises, draw international investment and so on. You’ve heard all this before and it sounds too much like your day job (if you could get a grip on what ‘day’ meant anymore through all the traveling you do). You are too excited about the evening and quickly turn the conversation to your potential purchase of the piece. You discuss with your friend which of your apartments the art would be best be best placed but you feel pretty clear that it should be where you will be spending the most time in the coming year. You often do this with new work so you can get to know it intimately, rewarding your sustained interest in it. Recognising however that by putting on this show the gallerist has pitched her space at the level of the international artscene rather than parochial interests, that the area was already being written about in several of the style guides you scanned on your iPad, and that the opening was busy enough not only with the usual ragbag of enthusiastic or sour local artists but also some people arriving in very statement cars, you also make a mental note to ask your friend soon about the local investment opportunities since something is clearly happening here.</p><p>Over dinner you are a bit relieved not to be sat to close to the artist since you still can’t get through her accent. But close enough to both her and the gallerist to not feel offended, you engage in interesting conversations with a couple of local collectors, artists and artcritics. They are interested in what you have to say about the artists work, your views on the other cities and artscenes you know well, and your thoughts on the development of the region in that context. One of the critics proposes interviewing you for their magazine, for a feature on the accessibility and importance of art collecting to developing the region’s cultural economy and identity in an age of globalization. You are flattered by this, feeling that she understands something of how we now all live in an interconnected world, how your interest in art expresses this inter-connectedness for you, allowing you to find something for yourself in relation to where you are and where the artists come from, what your respective interests are. You preview all this in your head as exchange cards with the critic, looking forward to showing her around your collection. Later, when you get a chance to talk more closely with the gallerist, you finalise the deal. It has been a very good evening and you leave it encouraged enough to even attempt a direct conversation with the artist as you leave</p><p>Two months later the piece is installed for you and on the few times you are in that apartment you find yourself becoming ever more enthusiastic about the artist’s ability to recall art’s most important values at such a personal and immediate level. You discuss your enthusiasm for the artist with your art advisor and he recommends you visit the artist’s home gallery with him to see what else they have available. Luckily, your business takes you to that city in the next month and he sets up the appointment for you. While there, you learn that nothing is available at this moment in time but the gallery will feature the artist in their next art-fair presentation. You express a strong interest and ensure that your schedule allows you to be there. Thanks to your relationship to the gallerist you initially dealt with, you secure a second piece at a discounted price at the fair’s pre-opening viewing session.</p><p>Three months after that: you secure another piece form the artist’s first show in New York. You can’t be there but your art advisor takes care of the details. You are pleased to learn that you are now one of the leading collectors of this artist’s work: you believe that she is worth standing behind, that her work deserves the exposure and attention it is getting in the magazines and journals, that her artistic intelligence and sensitivity accords not just with your own but also that of your colleagues and your friends who have mostly been impressed with her art, which you now have set up in more than one of your living spaces.</p><p>So it’s with genuine pleasure that you receive a request form the artist’s main gallery a year later to lend one of the works to a museum show in a major metropolitan center. You are especially excited because it is in one the cities where you spend the most time and you have appreciated for some time the museum’s exhibitions of traditional work from different regions curated with contemporary art. When you can get to these shows given your busy schedule you have seen have impressed with their commitment to finding an aesthetic and cultural merit in today’s world for these various traditions. You have no problem agreeing to the loan which you arrange through your art advisor. He secures a place for you and himself at the exclusive pre-public launch for the museum show.</p><p>Though you have some reservations as to whether the artist’s work has been best served by how it has been installed in the exhibition, you also recognize that its appearance in the show is very good for the artist’s profile. The artist herself is at once nervous and very excited to be in the show. Having by now come to understand her speech somewhat, you make small talk and share a few jokes with her to re-assure her during the formalities of the opening. At the dinner, you again find yourself speaking with enthusiasm about your appreciation for the artist, the exhibition and the museum, the need to promote awareness of histories and traditions of art and beyond in a globalized world, and how museums are very well suited for this since history is after all their business. You impress the Chair of the Museum’s Commissions Panel, whom you are pleased to learn already knows something about you. For all that, you are still a little surprised (and gratified) to receive an email from her a month or so later asking you to attend a lunch with friends of the Museum and its Director. At the lunch, the Director mentions that a space has recently emerged on the Board of Advisors and asks you to consider it. You are of course delighted to be asked but play it cool and tell him only that you will think about it. The Director mentions that any such appointment will all depend upon a formal invitation, a vetting procedure (for reasons of public accountability) and perhaps even a panel interview. This causes you a certain alarm. Should you have been less diffident in your response? You reassure yourself that these are standard processes that would have to be undertaken in any case. And indeed a week or so letter you receive a letter inviting you to be an Advisor to the Museum, asking for you to contribute to its future development on the basis of your keen interest in promoting contemporary art. You accept, going through the ritual processes of appointment with ease and comfort. Asked about why you would wish to take on the extra effort which comes with such little renumeration, you find yourself thinking of the art that brought you into contact with the museum in the first instance and this gives you the confidence to speak in real, substantial ways of your passion and belief in what art can do for individuals like yourself.</p><p>Very soon find yourself using your skills in investment and growth to advice the museum on its expansion strategy. This excites you since they seem especially respectful of the parameters that you think are important in art today: an emphasis on individual encounters with it, its opening to respectful debate, a strong educative aspect in its bringing important issues to people’s attention without being directing, inclusivity. What continues to inspire you through the sometimes dull but important work you are called onto do for the museum is that all of this is now at the core of the region’s growth strategy in which the museum is playing a central role. You play your modest yet important part in this. Promoting a public education that is appropriately sensitive to the complexities of the world by supporting what you find best about art, you feel you have fond something that represents you best in public, something worthwhile not just for yourself but for all of us.</p>[:]','[:sr]Zbog čega umetnost? Primarnost publike[:en]Why Art? The Primacy of Audience[:]','','publish','closed','closed','','zbog-cega-umetnost-primarnost-publike','','','2016-11-07 21:00:30','2016-11-07 21:00:30','',0,'http://www.zentmagazine.com/?post_type=zent&#038;p=269',0,'zent','',0),
